## 4. Performance & Safety Considerations

| Issue | Why it matters | Mitigation |
|-------|----------------|------------|
| **Speed** | Reflection involves metadata look‑ups and often uses `MethodInfo.Invoke`, which is slower than a direct call (roughly 10‑100× slower). | Cache `Type`, `MethodInfo`, `PropertyInfo` objects; use compiled delegates (`Expression<T>` or `Delegate.CreateDelegate`) for hot paths. |
| **Security** | Reflection can bypass accessibility (e.g., `BindingFlags.NonPublic`) and modify private fields, which may break encapsulation or expose sensitive data. | Use `ReflectionPermission` (in older .NET) or limit usage to trusted code; avoid exposing reflection APIs in public libraries. |
| **Versioning** | Code that relies on member names or signatures can break when the target assembly changes. | Prefer attribute‑driven contracts or interfaces; write defensive code that checks for existence before invoking. |
| **AOT / trimming** | Ahead‑of‑time compiled platforms (e.g., .NET Native, iOS, trimming in .NET 6+) may remove members that appear unused, causing reflection to fail at runtime. | Add `DynamicDependency` or `Preserve` attributes, or use the `rd.xml`/`linker` configuration to keep needed members. |
| **Nullability & type safety** | Reflection returns `object`; you must cast manually, risking `InvalidCastException`. | Use `as`/`is` checks, or better, generate strongly‑typed delegates via `Expression` trees. |

