## 5. Alternatives & Complementary Techniques

| Technique | When it replaces reflection | Notes |
|-----------|----------------------------|-------|
| **`dynamic` (C# 4+)** | When you need late‑bound calls but want cleaner syntax. | The DLR still uses reflection under the hood; performance similar to `MethodInfo.Invoke`. |
| **Expression trees (`System.Linq.Expressions`)** | When you need high‑performance, compiled delegates for property getters/setters or method calls. | You can compile an `Expression` once and reuse it; speeds approach static calls. |
| **Source generators** | When you can generate the required code at compile time (e.g., mapping, serialization). | Zero runtime cost, but requires build‑time tooling. |
| **`System.Text.Json` / `System.Xml.Serialization`** | For common serialization scenarios, use the built‑in serializers that already use reflection internally but expose a simple API. | Avoid writing your own reflection‑based serializer unless you have special needs. |
| **`Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection`** | A DI container that internally uses reflection to resolve constructors, but you interact with it via high‑level abstractions. | Use the container rather than raw reflection for typical DI scenarios. |

